## AI SDK

Last couple of years, a lot of "definitive AI library / framework" claims have been made.

I have used several of them, and intensively used Langchain. It did the trick for a while, but as AI models incorporate certain features natively, the complexity that Langchain brought to the stack was less and less necessary. In my opinion, it's also a bit too abstract.

For simple tools, I now stick to AI SDK. For complex tools, I may either code a solution myself leveraging the AI SDK features, or go back to Langchain if that's gonna save me (or the client) a lot of time (or money).

For example: A client asked me to create an AI assistant that was able to ingest and understand

## Puppeteer

Puppeteer gives you programmatic control over a headless (or full) Chrome browser so you can navigate pages, take screenshots, click buttons and basically do everything a "human" would be able to do on a website.

Learning how to use it was - to say the least - an interesting process, especially in a case where I need several instances running in parallel that need to be properly rotated after certain uses.

Thanks to using Puppeteer, I learned to use tools such as btop and got a better understanding of processes and garbage collection :)

## Other tools I use

- **Cursor**: obviously
- **PostHog**: As they put it "Product OS". Today an essential tool for me, especially in the first phase of any project.

I will keep this post updated whenever I find a relevant change in my stack 😊
